vine 1.2.0
prefix: ssm
title: Scout source management
---
[ssm] Generalize scout source onboarding and indexing (planning)
Two Scout commands replace the current per-vendor pattern (a bespoke
fetch_modal_docs.py-shaped script per source, a hand-added tuple in
search.py's DOCS_SOURCES, a manual search.py --update run): a batch mutation
command for as many or as few source operations as the caller needs. Every
caller-provided desired origin locator maps to exactly one source declaration and
never fans out; every operation receives one outcome record. A fetch-bearing
mutation targeting an existing source is an explicit re-fetch request even
when it remains fresh; and a
separate refresh-stale command that re-fetches and re-indexes every
already-registered source whose TTL has expired, replacing today's
read-the-warning-then-copy-the-refresh-command manual loop. Neither command
uses materialized content to discover an additional origin. Both commands need
representation on the CLI and as an MCP tool.
The Scout store is self-describing and has exactly two states: valid when every
declared invariant of its current publication and required checked-in
configuration holds, or invalid otherwise. A complete validation pass either
admits indexed answers or returns every violated invariant and no indexed
answers. A failed private candidate or fetch attempt does not alter a valid
current publication.
Every observed validation error is an instance of Scout's canonical closed
error discriminated union. Its discriminator selects the required evidence and
repair instruction for that error type; the complete error collection is the
self-describing repair response.
Source rows are design-time proposals, not runtime mutations. Scout validates
the complete ordered row list before fetch, intent, ledger write, or
publication, and returns every failed row. The only public row operations are
immutable-name `add`, a complete-declaration upsert, and target-only `remove`,
which reports whether it removed a declaration or found none. While the current
store is invalid, normal additions and removals are blocked until someone
restores validity from the complete error collection.
Vine graphs are repository-authored planning artifacts scout never indexes
today; add them as first-class chunked material alongside the existing indexed
repository material, using structural (per-task) chunking rather than raw word
windows, since a task is already the natural retrievable unit.
-> ssm/design/attempt-diagnostics
-> ssm/design/batch-atomicity
