> Scout has one source model: a declaration binds provenance to materialization,
> refresh, chunking, validity, and publication. Origin, representation, and
> local path choose adapter mechanics only; they do not create distinct source
> categories, namespaces, reader routes, or lifecycle contracts.
> Store validity is binary: every current-publication and required checked-in configuration invariant validates, or indexed answers are suppressed and the complete error collection is returned.
> A failed private candidate or fetch attempt does not alter a valid current publication.
> Every reported validation error is a value of the canonical closed error discriminated union; its discriminator selects the required evidence and repair instruction.
> Source rows are fully validated before runtime work; every failed row is returned and reaches no fetch, staging, ledger, or publication path.
> Public source rows are immutable-name `add` upserts and target-only `remove`; no public update or rename exists.
> An invalid current store blocks normal additions and removals until it is restored from its self-described failure report.
