[ssm/design/source-artifact-contract] Design source descriptor-to-artifact contract (reviewing)
The physical sources.json ledger is generic; every caller enters through the
single access boundary designed in ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary. This
contract governs every source registered through Scout's source-management
commands: each retains the fixed declaration together with current state; there
is no separate descriptor entity and no additional public source fields. The
declaration's origin locator and materialization/reconciliation behavior are
owned by ssm/design/source-origin-locator. That one contract applies to remote
and repository-local origins; neither an origin URL nor a repository glob is a
separate source model. Every managed source resolves deterministically to an
artifact root beneath resources/<safe-name> and to the current Scout
publication; ssm/design/source-artifact-path owns the safe-name derivation and
any path move semantics. Its required mime names the expected content
representation; it is neither an origin protocol nor the independent chunk-
adapter kind introduced in ssm/design/chunk-adapters. Remote HTTPS admission
applies when the selected materializer retrieves a remote origin. Each caller-
provided remote origin is one source: Scout may follow its permitted redirects
but stages only that final response as one artifact. It never treats a response
as a catalog, follows links from it, or expands one source into additional
sources.
The materializer returns a successful result only after staging a validated
candidate manifest with its artifact path, byte count, SHA-256, observed MIME,
and the origin-resolution evidence settled by
ssm/design/source-origin-locator. A staged candidate is not a live source
snapshot and cannot enter indexed
material discovery or be returned by search. Failure is a separate attempt outcome and
cannot masquerade as either a staged candidate or a live snapshot. This
contract is consumed by the ledger, lifecycle, admission, and command-surface
designs.
Accept: the owner confirms how every registered source resolves to one artifact
location, one current-publication membership, and one materialization-result
shape.
-> ssm/design/source-origin-locator
> The fixed declared row is name, origin locator, mime, and ttl_days; mime is the expected media type.
> Remote fetch admission accepts HTTPS origins only; transport is not encoded in mime and does not classify the source.
> Every managed source materializes beneath resources/<safe-name> and participates in the current Scout publication; the safe-name mapping and path move semantics are settled by ssm/design/source-artifact-path.
> One caller-provided remote origin is one source and stages one final response artifact; no catalog expansion, link discovery, crawl, or vendor-specific fan-out exists.
> A successful materialization returns a validated staged candidate manifest: artifact path, bytes, SHA-256, observed MIME, and origin-resolution evidence; a candidate is not query-visible.
> Failure is separate from a staged candidate and a live snapshot.
> Chunk kind is a separate local indexing concern and never reuses the source mime field.
---
[ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary] Design authoritative ledger access boundary (reviewing)
resources/sources.json is one generic source ledger. Every current and future
caller uses the same authoritative physical-ledger access boundary; no source
category has a separate writer, lock, journal, or recovery protocol. The generic
persistence contract is: an add applies directly through the locked atomic-write
path; an update or remove first durably records its intent; and every later
ledger access detects a present journal before returning a ledger view that
conflicts with it. The approved physical representation is a sibling intent
journal beside sources.json: sources.json remains the last committed readable
ledger, while the journal is the separately durable, recoverable pending
update/remove instruction.

Every access locks the pair only for ledger/journal read, write, and durable
recovery-state transition. It never runs remote materialization, index
construction, or publication rebase while that lock is held.
ssm/design/ledger-publication-recovery-handoff owns the executor claim/handoff,
non-owner behavior, and final replay/delete condition when a journal requires
source publication. This task does not select batch commit semantics; the journal
may carry the batch intent settled in ssm/design/batch-atomicity. It also owns
migration of current direct freshness.stamp-style writers onto the one generic
API, but not each caller's source declaration or publication semantics.
Accept: the approved sibling-journal boundary gives all callers direct atomic
add and durable update/remove intent/claim primitives, no two independently
implemented writers can mutate the physical ledger or bypass recovery, and no
external work can hold the ledger lock.
-> ssm/design/foundation-diagnostics
> sources.json remains one generic source ledger.
> Every ledger writer uses one authoritative access and recovery boundary.
> Adds apply directly through a locked atomic write.
> Updates and removes durably record intent before atomic application; a later ledger access detects a pending journal and enters the settled recovery handoff before serving a conflicting view.
> Intent storage is a sibling journal: sources.json is committed data; the journal is a pending update/remove instruction.
> The ledger lock covers only ledger/journal state transition; the recovery handoff owns external work and the final publication replay/delete condition.
---
[ssm/design/source-registry] Design the source ledger and its CRUD operations (planning)
Redefine the source registry as a single ledger -- sources.json's existing
fetched-state role absorbs the registry too; there is no separate descriptor
entity. Physical access to that generic ledger is settled by
ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary. Each source record retains the fixed declared
row: name, origin locator, required
mime (the expected content media type), ttl_days, plus either no live snapshot
or exactly one committed live snapshot. A candidate, partial artifact,
in-progress materialization, or index-not-yet-published artifact is not a
representable live source state. Freshness is derived from a committed snapshot's
timestamp, not stored as a mutable source-state flag. Origin transport and the
local chunk kind are separate concerns; there is no default protocol value in the declared
row and no per-source fetch-strategy field. The declared `name` is immutable
source identity. Callers submit an ordered proposed batch of `add` and `remove`
rows. Before runtime work, validation interprets every row in order against a
virtual registry, returns every failed row, and leaves virtual state unchanged
for each rejected row. `add` carries a complete declaration: an absent name
plans registration and an existing name plans declaration replacement plus an
explicit re-fetch. `remove` names only its immutable target and reports either
`removed` or `not_found`. There is no public `update` or rename. Each row
identifies exactly one source and receives exactly one outcome record; no row
discovers, creates, or fetches another source. A caller-provided desired origin
locator remains one declaration, never a fan-out mechanism. The validator performs
no fetch, staging, physical-ledger mutation, or publication. While the current
store is invalid, normal proposal application is blocked; repair ownership
belongs to the health and refetch designs. Pure preflight still runs while the
store is invalid: its reply contains every failed row with every applicable
error-union value, plus the complete store error collection, while rows
otherwise accepted by preflight remain unapplied.
ssm/design/batch-atomicity owns whether row mutations commit independently or
as one batch, including whether an otherwise valid subset may proceed after
preflight returns failed rows. The ledger stays small by design -- every access
reads and locks the whole file, no partial or indexed access. An accepted `add`
plan may register a declaration, not claim that its artifact has fetched or its
index has published; ssm/design/source-lifecycle owns those later states. The
generic ledger-access boundary applies its durable intent/claim primitives to
declaration replacement and removal. The recovery handoff owns selection of one
publication executor. Recovery never directly deletes or replaces a reader-
visible source row: it enters the same publication/removal transaction until
the declaration, live snapshot, and indexed-material membership agree. An
interruption leaves the intent behind; a later access detects and claims or
joins the settled handoff rather than serving a conflicting state or duplicating
external work.
The durable intent needs a representation that stays readable and recoverable
on every access; a raw append to a standalone JSON object cannot itself be
that representation. The intent/recovery journal is separate from the live
snapshot record and cannot point readers at a candidate. The settled generic
ledger-access boundary owns physical writer migration, locking, and persistence
primitives; the recovery handoff owns cross-boundary replay. This task consumes
them to define source records and proposals. Batch commit semantics belong only
to ssm/design/batch-atomicity.
Deterministic mapping from that identity to an artifact path, including path
collision and rename/move semantics, belongs only to
ssm/design/source-artifact-path.
Needs failure/timeout configuration (lock-wait duration, retry policy) for
ledger access -- see ssm/design/scout-config. Freshness selection must be a
structured result shared by refresh and warning presentation, not a refresh
parser for user-facing warning strings.
-> ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary
-> ssm/design/ledger-publication-recovery-handoff
-> ssm/design/scout-config
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
-> ssm/design/source-publication-boundary
---
[ssm/design/source-artifact-path] Design source identity to artifact-path mapping (reviewing)
Source names are lowercase ASCII `[a-z][a-z0-9-]{0,63}`. Their safe artifact root is exactly `resources/scout-source--<name>`, making the mapping total, one-to-one, stable, and case-safe on Windows. Each committed snapshot lives beneath `<root>/generations/<snapshot-id>/content`; `<snapshot-id>` is an opaque publication-qualified generation identifier. Candidate bytes are staged beneath the same root but never referenced by a publication until validation and index construction succeed. An `add` replacement retains old committed generations until no retained publication references them; a remove only makes a source unqueryable through a next publication, then cleanup may reclaim unreachable generations. No operation may traverse, rename, or delete another source root.
Accept: deterministic fixtures prove distinct valid names map to distinct roots, an upsert gives the same source identity a new generation without changing its root, and removal/recovery cannot affect another source's artifacts.
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
-> ssm/design/source-registry
> Valid source names are lowercase ASCII `[a-z][a-z0-9-]{0,63}`.
> Artifact root is exactly `resources/scout-source--<name>`; snapshot content is generation-qualified beneath that root.
> Replacement/removal retain generations referenced by any retained publication and reclaim only unreachable generations.
---
[ssm/design/batch-atomicity] Design source batch commit semantics (reviewing)
A proposal first preflights every row against a virtual registry. Any rejected row yields its row diagnostics; if one or more rows are rejected, no runtime work occurs for any row. `remove` of an absent name is a successful `not_found` outcome and leaves virtual state unchanged. If preflight accepts every row, Scout stages every fetch-bearing add and prepares the one resulting indexed-material generation. A materialization/index/publication failure prevents the entire batch from committing: the failed row reports its reached stage and diagnostic, while every otherwise staged row reports `not_committed` with the batch failure reference. Only one successful publication commits the full accepted virtual registry; every add then reports `published`, every existing remove reports `removed`, and every absent remove reports `not_found`. Interrupted accepted work remains one journal operation and later recovery completes or reports the same batch; no valid subset commits independently.
Accept: one client-visible batch result has exactly one outcome per input row; rejected proposals have no runtime trace; runtime failure commits no subset; and successful outcomes imply the source declaration, snapshot, and indexed-material membership crossed one publication together.
-> ssm/design/source-publication-boundary
-> ssm/design/source-registry
> Preflight is all-or-nothing: any rejected row prevents runtime work for every row.
> Accepted rows publish as one atomic batch; fetch/index/publication failure commits no subset and returns `not_committed` outcomes for otherwise staged rows.
> `remove` of an absent name is a successful `not_found` outcome, not a rejected row.
---
[ssm/design/source-publication-boundary] Design the source publication boundary (planning)
The approved reader model is a master publication pointer. It names one
immutable publication generation that binds the Scout source-state snapshot,
one live artifact generation or no snapshot per source, and the corresponding
indexed-material generation. Once the source control plane takes public-query
ownership, every public search reader resolves this master pointer first;
sources.json remains the generic mutation/recovery ledger and is not
independent query truth. A descriptor update is not reader-visible until its
candidate artifact and indexed-material membership are ready; removal is not
reader-visible until its old membership is absent. The ledger mutation journal
may record a desired change, but replay must route through this boundary rather
than directly replacing or deleting a reader-visible row.

The current master publication and strict checked-in Scout configuration are
the self-describing Scout-store validity boundary. The manifest declares every
reader-visible source state, artifact reference and digest, and indexed-material
generation and digest; configuration declares its own strict schema. The store
is valid exactly when complete validation finds no violated declared invariant.
Otherwise it is invalid: public search readers return no indexed answers and the
validator returns every violation. A failed fetch, staged candidate, or invalid
candidate remains private to its originating attempt and does not invalidate an
already-valid current publication.

Candidate generations are immutable and unreachable until the master pointer
changes. The initial cut retains prior complete generations conservatively;
cleanup is not a publication prerequisite. A missing, malformed, or internally
inconsistent master publication is an invalid-store validation result rather
than a reason to scan sibling artifacts or index generations for a plausible
fallback.

The physical boundary is `resources/.scout-publications/`: `CURRENT` contains
one opaque publication id, atomically replaced only after its immutable
`generations/<id>/manifest.json` is fully written and flushed. A manifest is
self-contained: schema version, publication id, parent id, the complete
reader-visible Scout source-state snapshot keyed by source identity, one
generation-qualified artifact reference and digest or no-snapshot state per
source, and the referenced indexed-material generation and digest. The master
publication pointer is the only public search reader entrypoint. An internal
index generation may retain a local `CURRENT`, but no route-specific pointer is
written or read as independent publication truth.

Each candidate names the master publication from which it was staged.
Fetching, artifact staging, and index construction occur outside the short
publication commit lock. Under that lock, a candidate whose base is still
current publishes by atomically flipping the master pointer. If another
publication won first, the control plane automatically rebases the already-
staged source mutation onto the newer complete publication, builds the
necessary next index generation outside the lock, and retries commit until it
publishes. Rebase contention never discards a valid staged mutation; a process
interruption leaves the ledger intent pending, and the settled recovery handoff
resumes the same rebase procedure. An invalid candidate artifact, index, or
manifest fails its private attempt and cannot become current.
Accept: after an interruption at any point, a reader can resolve only the
prior declaration with its prior snapshot and index membership, or the next
complete set, never a new declaration with old results or a removed declaration
with retained results.
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
> After source-control-plane activation, public search readers resolve one master publication pointer, not raw sources.json, artifact roots, and route-specific index CURRENT pointers independently.
> One immutable publication generation binds the Scout source-state snapshot, artifact generations, and indexed-material generation.
> Candidate generations are unreachable until publication; initial cleanup retains prior complete generations conservatively.
> The current master publication and strict checked-in configuration self-describe every Scout-store validity invariant; validation accumulates every violation before indexed answers are admitted or suppressed.
> A violated current-publication invariant makes the whole Scout store invalid and yields zero indexed answers; an invalid private candidate leaves a valid current publication valid.
> Readers never infer a fallback by scanning sibling generations.
> A stale staged candidate automatically rebases its source mutation onto the latest complete publication before retrying the short commit.
> `resources/.scout-publications/CURRENT` atomically names one immutable, self-contained generation manifest; it is the only public search reader entrypoint.
> Publication rebase continues until commit; interruption preserves the ledger intent so the settled recovery handoff resumes rather than abandons the valid staged mutation.
---
[ssm/design/docs-index-entrypoints] Design the sole source-index entry point (notstarted)
Given the source publication boundary, define the one permitted path through
which source chunks are built and published. A generic `resources/search.py`
`--update` or `--rebuild`, a missing-CURRENT cold build during a direct CLI
query, a missing-CURRENT cold build during resident-worker startup, or any
legacy route-specific code path must never independently publish indexed-material membership:
a direct bypass attempt fails loudly with the settled public repair path. The
source control plane is the sole index writer and routes every publication,
including recovery replay and initial index creation, through the source
publication boundary.
Define the corresponding sole public-search health gate too: normal CLI, JSON
CLI, and resident-worker/MCP routes must each resolve hits through the same
complete current-publication validation before ranking or output. The gate
accumulates every violated declared invariant. A valid result admits all indexed
hits to ranking; an invalid result returns no indexed hits and the complete
failure error collection. No public query path may return raw semantic or
keyword hits around that gate.
Before legacy conversion, apply the settled source-bound initial-publication
contract rather than treating aggregate legacy artifacts as source-bound
snapshots. The implementation migration replaces rather than layers beside the
current generic `Corpus` path: after cutover no public reader or publisher uses
a route-specific `CURRENT` as independent truth. Reads resolve the master
publication manifest to its referenced index generation; versions named by
retained publication manifests are not generic-cleanup candidates.
Before activation, this entrypoint stages no aggregate master publication:
generic update, rebuild, and cold-build paths never rebuild mutable aggregate
artifacts, and the source control plane exposes no public reader. The preexisting
legacy runtime is not a compatibility branch of this entrypoint. At activation,
the entrypoint takes public-query ownership through the first fully source-bound
publication and returns its migration repair action for rejected legacy writer
calls.
Accept: the owner confirms direct CLI and internal-call behavior that makes an
out-of-boundary publication or raw query architecturally unavailable, and makes
whole-store validation the only gate before indexed answers.
-> ssm/design/legacy-docs-precutover
-> ssm/design/mime-representation
-> ssm/design/source-diagnostics
-> ssm/design/source-hit-provenance
-> ssm/design/source-publication-boundary
---
[ssm/design/source-lifecycle] Design source live-snapshot publication lifecycle (notstarted)
Apply the state-space entropy ladder to artifact and index publication. A
registered source has only two query-visible states: no live snapshot, or one
committed live snapshot. A live snapshot is introduced only by a complete
publication that includes its validated artifact and makes it searchable; the
representation has no live variant for partial bytes, a staged candidate, an
unindexed artifact, or an index entry without its artifact. Candidates remain
outside corpus discovery and query-visible indexes until that publication.

An explicit re-fetch or refresh creates a separate attempt, never a mutation
of the current live snapshot. Failure or interruption leaves the prior live
snapshot unchanged when one exists; for a source with no prior snapshot it
leaves no live snapshot. For refresh selection, a registered source with no
live snapshot is structurally absent regardless of TTL and is eligible for
refresh-stale. A failed refresh with a usable prior snapshot produces a
non-live attempt diagnostic record; ssm/design/attempt-diagnostics owns its
storage, lifetime, and clearing behavior. It cannot become a query-visible
source state. Removal commits to no live snapshot only when the source is no
longer queryable. The owner decides the concrete
state transition and outcome projection using the concrete publication boundary
settled in ssm/design/source-publication-boundary. This task does not choose a
second transaction mechanism; every reader must observe either the prior
complete publication or the next complete publication, never a cross-artifact
mixture.
Diagnostics are a read-time projection of this resolution, not a third stored
source state. A stale but otherwise validating current publication, or a failed
private refresh attempt that leaves its committed snapshot valid, may produce a
warning. Any failure to validate a declared current-publication invariant makes
the whole Scout store invalid: it returns no indexed answers and the complete
failure report. A reader admits no partial, candidate, unindexed, or
artifact/index-mismatched material; it either admits the fully validated
current publication or no indexed material. The downstream verification task proves
that binary result under deterministic failures.
-> ssm/design/fresh-source-refetch
-> ssm/design/source-publication-boundary
-> ssm/design/source-registry
---
[ssm/design/attempt-diagnostics] Design non-live fetch-attempt diagnostics (notstarted)
A failed refresh with a valid prior snapshot must remain visible as a warning
on later public searches, but failures are not source snapshot states. Given the
ledger and lifecycle contracts, design the non-live attempt record: its binding
to a source and committed snapshot, durable location, retention, recovery, and
the exact event that clears or supersedes it. The record must not make a
candidate, failed attempt, or partial artifact discoverable as a live source.
Accept: the owner confirms how a failed refresh warning survives long enough
to be actionable, then clears or changes only through an unambiguous later
attempt outcome without changing the visible snapshot prematurely.
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
-> ssm/design/source-registry
---
[ssm/design/source-hit-provenance] Design source-to-hit provenance and filtering (notstarted)
Given the source publication lifecycle, define the stable binding carried by
each indexed chunk and search hit: source identity plus the committed
snapshot generation or manifest identity that produced it. Before ranking, the
whole-store validator resolves every required binding against the current
publication boundary and accumulates all absent-source, stale-generation, and
integrity failures. Any failure invalidates the Scout store and returns no
indexed hits. The owner decides the exact index metadata/id shape and validation
path without weakening this all-or-nothing gate. That validation is invoked by
every public search entry point, including normal CLI, JSON CLI, and the
resident worker used by MCP; no route may format or return unvalidated hits.
The binding occupies the canonical adapter tag envelope alongside `citation`;
the query path hydrates those tags from the loaded index generation before
filtering, ranking, or formatting. There is no second provenance sidecar or
reader-time inference from index ids/artifact paths.
Accept: one or more orphaned, stale-generation, or integrity-invalid fixtures
yield zero indexed hits and every corresponding validation failure, while a
fully valid store remains searchable.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
---
[ssm/design/source-diagnostics] Design actionable source-health diagnostics (reviewing)
Scout's canonical closed diagnostic code space extends the foundation codes unchanged. Source/materialization codes are `ORIGIN_INVALID`, `ORIGIN_NOT_FOUND`, `SOURCE_NAME_INVALID`, `SOURCE_ROW_INVALID`, `DESTINATION_DENIED`, `DESTINATION_RESOLUTION_FAILED`, `FETCH_CONNECT_FAILED`, `FETCH_REDIRECT_DENIED`, `FETCH_RESPONSE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED`, `FETCH_MIME_MISMATCH`, `FETCH_CHARSET_INVALID`, `FETCH_UTF8_INVALID`, and `MATERIALIZATION_FAILED`. Publication/store codes are `PUBLICATION_MISSING`, `PUBLICATION_MALFORMED`, `PUBLICATION_INTEGRITY_FAILED`, `INDEX_MISSING`, `INDEX_INTEGRITY_FAILED`, `SOURCE_BINDING_FAILED`, and `LEGACY_MIGRATION_REQUIRED`. Each code has exactly `{code,evidence,repair}` and code-specific evidence keys in the implementation registry. Warnings are separate typed values: `SNAPSHOT_STALE` and `REFRESH_FAILED`; they are allowed only when the current publication validates. No error path returns an untyped catch-all or parses display text back into state.
Accept: every source, materialization, publication, and store failure producer maps to one listed diagnostic code with required evidence/repair; an invalid store returns the complete collection unchanged; valid-store warnings remain typed and non-invalidating.
-> ssm/design/attempt-diagnostics
-> ssm/design/foundation-diagnostics
-> ssm/design/remote-destination-admission
-> ssm/design/source-hit-provenance
-> ssm/design/source-lifecycle
> Foundation codes remain unchanged; the listed source/materialization/publication codes complete the v1 closed diagnostic space.
> Every diagnostic serializes exactly `{code,evidence,repair}` with code-specific evidence keys.
> `SNAPSHOT_STALE` and `REFRESH_FAILED` are the only v1 warnings and are visible only for a valid current publication.
---
[ssm/design/fetch-admission] Design remote fetch admission and resource policy (reviewing)
Given the source descriptor-to-artifact contract, decide the rules enforced
before Scout fetches a caller-supplied remote origin. HTTPS is the only
accepted scheme. Redirects are limited to five and every target must retain
both HTTPS and the origin's host. The declared and observed base MIME types
must match and be either `text/plain` or `text/markdown`; an absent charset is
UTF-8 and an explicit charset must be UTF-8. Any MIME/charset mismatch,
unsupported MIME, or invalid UTF-8 response fails before candidate staging. The
owner has chosen the resource values: 60 seconds per request and 80 MiB per
response. One source stages exactly one final response artifact, so a separate
aggregate source-byte cap or file cap would duplicate the response bound or
imply prohibited fan-out. Those values, plus the redirect-count limit, are
checked-in Scout configuration; scheme/MIME/charset policy remains fixed. This
task owns enforcement policy. One shared bounded staging writer checks any
declared response length when available, counts streamed response bytes, and
removes the incomplete staging area on a limit breach. Command-surface design
only decides how callers supply a row and receive a rejected or failed outcome.
The settled policy must be usable by the shared control plane for both CLI and
MCP calls. Origin scheme and redirect-host policy do not by themselves admit an
actual connection target; ssm/design/remote-destination-admission owns that
separate policy, and this task consumes it for every remote connection hop.
Accept: the owner confirms the admission and resource contract, including how
each refused or exceeded limit is reported without claiming a lifecycle stage
that was not reached.
-> ssm/design/mime-representation
-> ssm/design/remote-destination-admission
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
> HTTPS is the only accepted origin scheme.
> Follow at most five redirects only when every redirect target remains HTTPS and has the original host.
> Destination admission is evaluated separately for every remote connection hop; scheme and original-host checks alone are insufficient.
> Require matching declared/observed text/plain or text/markdown MIME and UTF-8 charset; reject a mismatch before candidate staging.
> Scheme and MIME rules are fixed; request timeout, redirect count, and response-byte cap live in checked-in Scout config.
> One shared bounded staging writer enforces the configured response-byte limit, then removes incomplete staging on failure.
> The initial generic remote profile is 60 seconds per request and 80 MiB per response.
---
[ssm/design/https-single-url-materialization] Define one-URL HTTPS materialization (reviewing)
Each caller-provided URL is independently materialized as exactly one Scout
source. The generic HTTPS fetcher may follow only the admitted redirect chain,
then stages the final response as one artifact and emits its manifest. It does
not inspect a response for additional URLs, treat a document as a catalog,
crawl a site, or apply source-name/vendor-specific expansion. A batch of $n$
input URLs yields exactly $n$ independent source outcomes.
Accept: the owner confirms the one-URL-to-one-source staging boundary for
every registered HTTPS source.
-> ssm/design/fetch-admission
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
> Each input URL maps to one source, one final response artifact, and one outcome.
> Redirect handling is transport for that one URL, not source expansion.
> No catalog parsing, link discovery, crawl, or vendor-specific collection rule exists.
---
[ssm/design/mime-representation] Design MIME-to-indexable representation (reviewing)
Each source declares and validates a response MIME, but a successful fetch must
also have one settled route into the indexed chunk pipeline. The initial allowed
set is `text/plain` and `text/markdown`, with an absent charset interpreted as
UTF-8 and an explicit charset required to be UTF-8. Fetch decodes the response
strictly as UTF-8, preserving its bytes and observed MIME/digest in the source
artifact manifest. Both MIME types use the canonical textual representation and
the default text chunk adapter; Markdown does not receive special structural
parsing in this cut. A different observed or declared MIME, unsupported MIME,
or invalid text encoding fails at admission with an actionable diagnostic
before staging or publication. This design owns representation selection, not
source discovery; one URL still yields one response artifact.
Accept: each initially allowed MIME produces searchable text chunks through the
default adapter, while every unsupported MIME or encoding fails with an
actionable diagnostic before publication.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-contract
> Initial allowed MIME set: text/plain and text/markdown, decoded strictly as UTF-8.
> Both allowed types use the default text chunk adapter; no HTML, PDF, or other conversion is implied by this remote text profile. Legacy migration must explicitly represent or retire other material rather than route it through another source category.
> MIME or encoding mismatch fails before candidate staging/publication.
---
[ssm/design/legacy-docs-migration] Design migration of current indexed material (notstarted)
The current implementation has category-specific material paths: the Modal pin
expands one llms.txt URL into hundreds of Markdown pages, the VS Code pin groups
two distinct raw Markdown URLs beneath one ledger record, the paper manifest
drives a separate PDF fetcher, and repository material is discovered directly
from local paths. The unified source model forbids retaining any of those paths
as a source-management bypass. The settled one-URL model forbids preserving the
Modal or VS Code fan-out by inference.
The owner decides the exact disposition of every currently indexed material item:
represent a retained remote origin as one declared source, represent retained
repository-local material through the same source contract, deliberately reduce
coverage to explicitly named material, or retire it. This task produces the
owner-confirmed retained declaration list and retirement list: source names,
origin locators, required MIME values, and planned artifact mapping. It does
not stage the initial publication, implement provenance/index construction, or
define the public query gate; those downstream owners consume its disposition.
Do not let the implementation infer a catalog rule or a category exception merely
to preserve today’s coverage.
Accept: the owner confirms the exact disposition and retained declaration list
for every current source before its legacy writer, aggregate record, or direct-
discovery bypass is retired.
-> ssm/design/https-single-url-materialization
-> ssm/design/mime-representation
-> ssm/design/source-artifact-path
-> ssm/design/source-hit-provenance
-> ssm/design/source-origin-locator
-> ssm/design/source-publication-boundary
-> ssm/design/source-registry
