[ssm/design/legacy-docs-precutover] Design source-bound initial publication (planning)

After ssm/design/legacy-docs-migration produces the owner-confirmed retained
declaration list, this task designs the private source-bound initial candidate.
It consumes the source registry, publication boundary, provenance, diagnostics,
and origin-locator contracts to bind every retained artifact to one source. No
aggregate compatibility publication or unprovenanced compatibility reply becomes
reader-visible. The existing legacy runtime is the pre-activation program, not
a control-plane reader or compatibility mode. No control-plane public route is
deployed until this candidate is complete. Activation replaces the legacy public
reader with the master pointer as the first public source publication.

The initial candidate validates through the settled manifest, source-binding,
and diagnostic contracts. This task does not decide retained coverage or the
public query gate: migration owns the former, while
ssm/design/docs-index-entrypoints consumes the candidate to define the latter.
A failed candidate is private and does not create a partial public source state.
After the atomic cutover, legacy fetch scripts, direct-discovery paths, and
generic `--update`/`--rebuild` paths fail loudly with the settled migration
repair action rather than mutate indexed material outside the control plane.
Accept: the first master-published generation is fully source-bound; no public
master generation or answer contains aggregate or unprovenanced legacy material;
cutover adds no compatibility lifecycle beside the ordinary source publication
lifecycle; and no deployed public route exposes both reader models.
