[ssm/design/fresh-source-refetch] Define direct fresh-source refetch behavior (notstarted)
Given the settled source-operation identity, an `add` targeting an existing
source is an explicit re-fetch request even when its TTL has not expired. A
remove is target-only and never fetches. That behavior
belongs to the existing batch mutation command; it does not add a third public
command. refresh-stale remains the unattended maintenance path and selects
only stale or absent sources. A registered source with no live snapshot is
absent, so refresh-stale selects it without needing a TTL timestamp. The result
tells command-surface and control-plane work how to distinguish an explicit
re-fetch from automatic stale maintenance in their outcomes.
Accept: the owner confirms that a fetch-bearing direct mutation re-fetches a
fresh source, a remove does not, and refresh-stale does not re-fetch fresh
snapshots.
-> ssm/design/source-registry
> An `add` targeting an existing source is re-fetched even when fresh.
> refresh-stale remains stale/absent-only; no third public command is added.
> A registered source with no live snapshot is absent and refresh-stale selects it.
---
[ssm/design/vine-chunking] Design per-task chunking for vine files (planning)
Given the chunk-type-adapter interface from ssm/design/chunk-adapters, design VINE's adapter for an already materialized declared VINE source: parse its local artifact into task blocks (reusing Bacchus's VINE semantics only as far as a structural split needs: use the declared delimiter when present, otherwise `---`, then recognize task and ref headers). The indexer must not need a live MCP vine_read call or a full VINE parser. Apply the bounded task representation settled in ssm/design/vine-task-length.
Task citations are `<repo-relative-vine-path>#<task-id>#vine`, retaining an unambiguous file locator plus task id so a result can resolve through the settled repository-owned citation resolver even when VINE stems collide. This is the task resolver citation, not necessarily the unique index identity: long-task segments use distinct adapter index identities while sharing the one task citation. Ref blocks emit chunks as `<repo-relative-vine-path>#ref:<id>#vine`; their repository-owned resolution and test contract is designed in ssm/design/vine-citation-resolution rather than treating a ref proxy as a task. A ref chunk contains only its local proxy name and description. It never creates a source declaration, materializes a target, schedules target indexing, or derives target content. A referred VINE becomes indexable only through its own explicit source add row and materialization under ssm/design/source-origin-locator.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
-> ssm/design/source-origin-locator
-> ssm/design/vine-citation-resolution
-> ssm/design/vine-task-length
> Parse locally by splitting on a declared delimiter, or the default `---`, then recognizing task and ref headers; do not require a full VINE parser or live MCP call.
> Emit each task segment with a unique adapter index identity and the shared task resolver citation `<repo-relative-vine-path>#<task-id>#vine`.
> Emit ref chunks as `<repo-relative-vine-path>#ref:<id>#vine`; resolve them through the settled ref-aware citation contract rather than task lookup.
> A ref chunk indexes only its local proxy name and description; neither it nor its target URI creates a declaration, materialization, or indexing operation. A target VINE is indexable only through its own explicit source add row.
---
[ssm/design/vine-task-length] Design bounded VINE task chunking (complete)
The configured MiniLM sentence-transformer limit is 256 tokens including
special tokens, while a VINE task can exceed any word-based heuristic;
embedding an unbounded task as one string would rely on encoder truncation and
silently lose its tail. The approved representation first creates a canonical
searchable projection. For a task, it contains a field-labeled name and status
prologue followed by every decision text and description entry in their
physical task-body order. For a ref, it contains its field-labeled local proxy
name and local description. This projection preserves all words of those
selected searchable fields; task ids, file paths, segment ordinals, and resolver
citations stay in canonical tags. Dependencies, attachments, and a ref's target
graph content are deliberately outside the searchable projection, matching the
settled proxy-only ref scope.

The VINE-specific windower derives its content budget at runtime from the
configured embedding model's effective sequence limit minus its special-token
count; it never uses a word count as a safety proof. It packs contiguous spans
at whitespace boundaries whenever possible and verifies that each emitted span,
when encoded with special tokens, is within that effective limit. Adjacent
segments overlap by up to 30 content-token ids without exceeding either
segment's token budget. If one unbroken lexical run cannot fit a token-safe
span, the windower splits it at a Unicode character boundary chosen by the same
tokenizer check; no text is silently discarded or truncated. There is no generic
20-word minimum filter: every non-empty task/ref projection emits at least one
segment.

Segments have distinct adapter `index_id`s using the stable
`<citation>#s<ordinal>` suffix, while their canonical tag citation remains
`<repo-relative-vine-path>#<task-id>#vine` for a task or
`<repo-relative-vine-path>#ref:<id>#vine` for a ref. Thus a query can retrieve
a specific segment but a reader always resolves the one task or ref proxy. A
block that fits the budget emits one segment; a long block emits ordered
overlapping segments. No generated summary substitutes for selected searchable
field text.
Accept: a task or ref above the encoder-safe bound has no silently truncated
selected searchable text; every non-empty block emits a segment with a unique
index identity and resolves to its originating VINE task or ref proxy citation.
-> ssm/design/chunk-adapters
> Task projection: name/status then decision and description entries in physical body order; ref projection: local name and description.
> Preserve all words of selected searchable fields; dependencies, attachments, and ref target content remain outside the projection.
> Use a tokenizer-aware VINE window within the configured effective embedding limit, with up to 30 content-token ids of overlap and no minimum-length drop.
> Segment index ids carry stable ordinals; all task segments share one task citation and all ref segments share one ref citation.
> Do not summarize or discard selected searchable field text to fit the embedding budget.
---
[ssm/design/vine-citation-resolution] Design repository-owned VINE citation resolution (complete)
`resources/vine.py` is the repository-local structural parser and citation
resolver shared by Scout indexing and its executable tests. It parses only
the settled indexing subset: a declared delimiter or default `---`, then task
and ref headers. It returns structured local blocks for chunk projection and
resolves canonical citations without needing Bacchus, VS Code, or a live MCP
call. Bacchus remains the external authority for full VINE graph semantics;
this parser neither reimplements mutation nor validates unrelated graph rules.

The resolver accepts only normalized repo-relative `.vine` paths beneath the
repository root plus exactly one canonical task id or `ref:<id>` target. A task
citation resolves only a task header; a ref citation resolves only a ref header.
Malformed citation syntax, absolute/traversing paths, missing/non-VINE files,
unknown ids, and task/ref kind mismatches raise explicit typed resolution
failures. The indexing and citation test use the same resolver; smoke imports
it directly rather than depending on VS Code MCP configuration.
Accept: `python -m scout.smoke` exercises temporary task/ref VINE fixtures and
proves every emitted citation resolves to its intended local block while each
malformed or absent target fails explicitly.
> resources/vine.py owns the local structural parser and canonical citation resolver.
> Canonical paths are normalized repo-relative .vine paths; task and ref targets are kind-specific.
> The executable test invokes the local resolver directly, not vine_read or MCP.
---
[ssm/design/vine-corpus] Design VINE attachment to the unified source publication (planning)
VINE chunks are source material governed by the same provenance, refresh,
validity, and publication contract as every other indexed material. The current
workspace route is a legacy bypass and cannot establish a distinct reader or
publication state. Tags preserve explicit resolver citations so a result remains
distinguishable from prose without creating a separate source category.

The deterministic repository inventory remains root `*.vine` plus
`proposals/**/*.vine`, excluding no file by name. It is migration/audit input,
not direct index intake or declaration discovery: every retained VINE file must
appear as one explicit source `add` row with one concrete repository-local
origin locator. Later VINE additions use the same public add-row path; a glob
never creates rows or fans out into sources. ssm/design/source-origin-locator
owns validation and reconciliation of the declared locator to its immutable
identity, current snapshot, refresh observation, and removal behavior. Only
materialized declared VINE sources reach the `vine-task` adapter instead of the
generic word-window adapter.
Accept: every emitted VINE chunk binds to a declared source and committed
snapshot in the same source publication as all indexed material; root and
proposal VINE inventory is auditable against explicit declarations; and no route
label creates a separate corpus or publication surface.
-> ssm/design/source-origin-locator
-> ssm/design/vine-chunking
> VINE inventory is migration/audit input, not direct index intake or declaration discovery.
> Add one concrete repository-local VINE origin per explicit source row; a glob never creates rows or fans out.
> Dispatch only materialized declared VINE sources through the vine-task adapter, never generic word windows.
---
[ssm/implement/vine-indexing] Implement VINE parsing and unified source wiring (notstarted)
Retain `resources/vine.py` as the shared settled local structural parser and canonical citation resolver, then use it to host the VINE adapter designed in ssm/design/vine-chunking and migrate only explicit declared, materialized VINE source artifacts from the legacy `workspace_chunks()` route into the generic source pipeline per ssm/design/vine-corpus. Hydrated self-citations resolve through this module, the same way any source citation resolves back to its source material. The indexer does not invoke MCP or require an ambient VS Code service; it does not treat a ref proxy as a task, and a ref must never create, materialize, or index its target.

Add direct temporary-fixture resolver checks to `python -m scout.smoke` for task/ref citations plus malformed syntax, traversal/absolute path, missing file/id, and task/ref kind mismatch failures. Apply the settled bounded-task representation rather than relying on encoder truncation. Emit canonical adapter tags for every VINE segment; force a full source-index rebuild when upgrading from the prior text-only manifest schema, then verify that saved/reloaded index tags hydrate the resolving task/ref citations rather than raw unique index ids. Add a fixture proving a ref target remains absent from indexed material until that target is independently supplied by its own explicit source declaration and materialization.

Test task and ref projections above the encoder-safe bound so every emitted segment has a unique index identity, retains the one resolving citation, and preserves every word of the selected searchable fields in their prescribed order. Assert each emitted string encodes within the configured effective embedding limit, adjacent long segments preserve up to 30 content-token ids of overlap, and a token-dense unbroken lexical run uses the character-boundary fallback without text loss. Test short non-empty task and ref projections too, proving that the VINE-specific windower emits them rather than applying the generic 20-word minimum filter.
