[ssm/implement/source-control-plane] Implement the shared source control plane (notstarted)
Implement the settled config reader, source orchestration, structured
freshness state, and artifact-to-index lifecycle behind one local control-plane
interface. It consumes the authoritative shared ledger writer and recovery API
from ssm/implement/ledger-access-boundary; command implementations neither
manipulate the ledger nor derive staleness directly. It owns HTTPS fetch
dispatch, including the settled one-URL materialization for every
caller-supplied origin. It provides the common result shape for
control-plane-managed sources. Until legacy migration cuts over the current
material paths, those legacy writers remain outside this protocol;
ssm/implement/legacy-docs-migration owns their conversion and retirement. No
control-plane-managed source has a direct freshness.stamp mutation bypass.
Before activation, stage the settled source-bound initial publication privately:
the control plane exposes no public reader and does not delegate to the legacy
runtime. Generic update, rebuild, and cold-build paths cannot independently
publish aggregate artifacts, and legacy writers fail with their migration repair
action rather than mutate material outside the control plane. At activation, the
control plane takes every public query route through the master pointer. Enforce
the settled remote fetch-admission,
MIME-representation, and fresh-source-
refetch and batch-atomicity policies through this one interface rather than
duplicating concerns in a CLI or MCP wrapper. Respect the settled generic
ledger-access boundary: no operation bypasses the authoritative writer/recovery
protocol for the physical ledger. Construct a query-visible live snapshot only at
complete publication; a staged candidate and an attempt failure must be
unrepresentable as indexed-material input or search result. Validate the whole current
publication before any indexed answer: when every declared invariant holds, serve
ranked indexed hits; otherwise return zero indexed hits and the complete failure
report. Create, retain, and clear non-live fetch-attempt diagnostics only when
the current publication remains valid. At publication, bind every indexed chunk to
its source identity and committed snapshot generation or manifest identity;
never publish unbound chunks into the shared indexed material. Put that binding
and the resolver citation in canonical adapter tags, and force a full source-index rebuild
when upgrading the prior text-only manifest schema so no published generation
has partially missing tag metadata.
This is the sole index writer: every generic update/rebuild path in
resources/search.py, including a missing-CURRENT cold build from direct CLI or
resident-worker startup, delegates here or fails with the settled fatal repair
path; no legacy route-specific code path retains independent index maintenance.
Replace rather than layer beside the current generic legacy publisher: after
cutover public reads resolve only the master publication manifest to its
referenced index generation, never a route-specific `CURRENT`; generic cleanup
retains every index/artifact generation referenced by a retained master
publication and may reclaim only unreachable candidates or generations.
Stage source candidates outside the short publication commit lock and apply the
settled automatic rebase procedure when their base publication is stale; never
hold the ledger/publication lock across remote fetches or index construction.
Accept: the control plane is the authoritative path for all registered
one-URL sources and can report each row's lifecycle state without a direct
freshness.stamp bypass; every such mutation uses the settled authoritative
ledger boundary, and the generic HTTPS fetcher materializes each admitted
deterministic fixture as exactly one source artifact through that same path.
