[ssm/design/scout-config] Design where scout's own operational config lives (reviewing)
Scout operational configuration lives in checked-in `resources/scout.json`, separate from generic source data in `sources.json`. Its exact v1 JSON object is:
```
{"schema_version":1,"ledger":{"lock_wait_seconds":30,"lock_poll_milliseconds":100},"fetch":{"request_timeout_seconds":60,"max_redirects":5,"max_response_bytes":83886080}}
```
The root keys are exactly `schema_version`, `ledger`, and `fetch`; `ledger` and `fetch` have exactly the displayed keys. Every numeric value is an integer rather than bool. `schema_version` is exactly 1; wait, poll, timeout, and response bytes are positive; redirects are nonnegative; and `lock_poll_milliseconds <= lock_wait_seconds * 1000`. Missing, malformed, unknown-key, wrong-type, and invalid-domain cases return the foundation typed diagnostics. The source control plane, search worker, and CLI/MCP wrappers consume the same parsed configuration; environment variables and proxy settings do not override it. Destination policy has no v1 config fields.
Accept: config fixtures prove the exact nested shape and every rejection domain, return foundation diagnostics without defaults, and expose the parsed object unchanged to every consumer.
-> ssm/design/fetch-admission
-> ssm/design/foundation-diagnostics
-> ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary
-> ssm/design/remote-destination-admission
> V1 config shape is exactly `schema_version`, `ledger`, and `fetch` with the nested keys shown in the task description; unknown keys are rejected at every level.
> Config numerics are integers not bool; wait/poll/timeout/bytes are positive, redirects are nonnegative, and poll is no greater than wait in milliseconds.
> V1 destination policy has no config fields; configuration and proxy environment variables never override the checked-in object.
