[ssm/design/source-origin-locator] Design unified source-origin locator and reconciliation (reviewing)
One Scout source declaration carries an `origin` object with exactly one of two v1 shapes: `{"kind":"https","url":"https://..."}` or `{"kind":"repo-file","path":"relative/posix/path"}`. `https` has exactly `kind` and `url`; URL parsing rejects credentials, fragments, non-HTTPS schemes, absent hosts, and noncanonical textual forms. `repo-file` has exactly `kind` and `path`; its path is normalized repo-relative POSIX syntax, has no absolute/drive/traversal component, resolves beneath the repository root without a symlink/reparse escape, and names one regular file. A source declaration never carries a glob. `ttl_days` is either null for immutable material or a positive integer. Reconciliation consumes one explicit row and materializes only that locator; inventory globs remain migration/audit input and never create rows or fan out.
Accept: strict parser fixtures accept only the two shapes, reject locator ambiguity/escape/discovery, and show that each accepted locator materializes one reproducible source snapshot.
> V1 origin locators are structured objects: `https` with `url`, or `repo-file` with repo-relative `path`; unknown keys and kinds are rejected.
> `repo-file` resolves one regular file beneath the repository root after symlink/reparse resolution; globbing remains audit-only.
> `ttl_days` is null for immutable material or a positive integer; reconciliation consumes one explicit declaration and never discovers declarations.
---
[ssm/design/ledger-publication-recovery-handoff] Design ledger-publication recovery handoff (reviewing)
The generic ledger keeps one sibling journal and one generic executor lock at `sources.json.recovery.lock`. A caller detecting a journal first acquires the recovery executor lock under the configured wait/poll policy, then under the short ledger lock claims the journal by its immutable `operation_id` and records a durable phase. The executor lock, not the ledger lock, remains held while materialization, candidate persistence, index construction, and publication rebase run. A non-owner waits for journal disappearance or returns `LEDGER_BUSY`; it never serves a ledger view that conflicts with the journal. OS release of the executor lock after process death permits the next claimant to validate/reuse a persisted candidate manifest or rematerialize it if invalid. The journal records operation id, desired mutation, phase, candidate reference/digest when staged, and base/current publication identity. Publication is committed under the short publication lock; only after the master publication reflects the desired source state does the executor apply the ledger mutation and delete the journal under the short ledger lock. A claimant validates operation id/phase before every commit, fencing a stale claimant.
Accept: deterministic concurrent/crash fixtures prove one executor performs external work, a crashed executor can be taken over with a valid staged candidate, stale claimants cannot commit, and journal deletion follows both publication and ledger agreement.
-> ssm/design/ledger-access-boundary
-> ssm/design/source-publication-boundary
> A generic OS-held recovery executor lock serializes external recovery work; the ledger lock is never held across that work.
> The journal persists immutable operation id, desired mutation, durable phase, candidate reference/digest, and publication identity; claim validation fences stale executors.
> Publish first, then apply ledger state and delete the journal only after publication/ledger agreement; non-owners wait or receive `LEDGER_BUSY`.
---
[ssm/design/remote-destination-admission] Design remote destination admission (reviewing)
V1 remote destination admission is fixed, not configurable: Scout ignores proxy configuration and connects only directly. For every origin and redirect hop, a literal IP is parsed directly and a hostname is resolved once using `getaddrinfo`; every resolved candidate address must be `ipaddress.is_global`. A resolution with no addresses or any non-global address is denied. The fetcher pins the TCP connection to one approved resolved address, uses the URL hostname for TLS SNI and the Host header, and repeats resolution/admission for every redirect hop. It never lets the HTTP stack re-resolve a hostname after admission. `DESTINATION_DENIED` evidence includes origin host, candidate address when present, and denial reason; `DESTINATION_RESOLUTION_FAILED` and `FETCH_CONNECT_FAILED` remain typed source diagnostics. No destination fields are added to v1 Scout config.
Accept: deterministic fixtures prove literal/local, mixed-answer DNS, DNS-change, redirect-hop, and proxy-environment cases cannot connect to an unadmitted address, while an approved pinned address succeeds with hostname TLS.
-> ssm/design/source-origin-locator
> V1 uses no proxy and admits only globally routable resolved addresses; a mixed global/non-global resolution is denied.
> Every connection is pinned to an admitted address while preserving original-host TLS SNI and Host header; each redirect hop re-resolves and revalidates.
> Destination policy adds no v1 config fields; denied/resolution/connect outcomes use typed diagnostics.
---
[ssm/design/foundation-diagnostics] Design foundation diagnostics for config and ledger (reviewing)
Foundation diagnostics are the typed bootstrap boundary for strict configuration and generic ledger access. Every diagnostic is a serializable value with exactly `code`, `evidence`, and `repair`; display rendering is not state. The initial closed foundation code set is `CONFIG_MISSING`, `CONFIG_MALFORMED`, `CONFIG_UNKNOWN_KEY`, `CONFIG_WRONG_TYPE`, `CONFIG_INVALID_VALUE`, `LEDGER_BUSY`, `LEDGER_MALFORMED`, `LEDGER_JOURNAL_MALFORMED`, and `LEDGER_RECOVERY_FAILED`. Each code fixes its evidence keys and repair instruction in the implementation registry. `ScoutDiagnosticsError` may transport one or more values internally, but no foundation path raises or returns an untyped string error. ssm/design/source-diagnostics extends this same code/payload boundary for source/publication variants; it does not translate foundation diagnostics.
Accept: config and ledger code can return only the listed typed foundation diagnostics, and later public validation can aggregate those values unchanged with the completed source diagnostic union.
> Foundation diagnostic payload is exactly `{code, evidence, repair}`; rendered text is derived only at CLI/MCP presentation.
> Foundation codes are `CONFIG_MISSING`, `CONFIG_MALFORMED`, `CONFIG_UNKNOWN_KEY`, `CONFIG_WRONG_TYPE`, `CONFIG_INVALID_VALUE`, `LEDGER_BUSY`, `LEDGER_MALFORMED`, `LEDGER_JOURNAL_MALFORMED`, and `LEDGER_RECOVERY_FAILED`.
> Foundation diagnostics flow unchanged into the eventual canonical source diagnostic union; no bootstrap string/error side channel exists.
